25|$|Hansen et al. (2012) {{suggested}} that human activities have greatly increased {{the risk of}} summertime <b>heat</b> <b>waves.</b> According to their analysis, the land area of the Earth affected by very hot summer temperature anomalies has greatly increased over time (refer to graphs on the left). In the base period 1951-1980, these anomalies covered a few tenths of 1% of the global land area. In recent years, this has increased to around 10% of the global land area. With high confidence, Hansen et al. (2012) attributed the 2010 Moscow and 2011 Texas <b>heat</b> <b>waves</b> to human-induced global warming.|$|E
